The '''''Painting of the Six Kings''''' is a [[fresco]] found on the wall of [[Qasr Amra]], a [[desert castles|desert castle]] of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]] located in modern-day [[Jordan]]. It depicts six rulers standing in two rows of three.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=198}}{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}} Four of the six have inscriptions in [[Arabic]] and [[Greek language|Greek]] identifying them as the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] emperor, King [[Roderic]] of [[Hispania]], the [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] emperor, and the [[Negus]] of [[Kingdom of Aksum|Aksum]].<ref name="met">{{harvnb|Williams|2012}}</ref>{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}}{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=205}} The painting, now substantially damaged, is thought to be from between 710 and 750,{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=121}} commissioned by the Umayyad [[caliphate|caliph]] or someone in his family.{{sfn|Grabar|1954|p=187}} It is one of the most famous frescoes in the Qasr Amra complex.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=197}}

==Location and history==
[[File:Qusayr Amra.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Qasr Amra]] complex, the site of the painting]]
[[File:AloisMusil1901.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Alois Musil, the first Westerner who encountered the painting.{{sfn|Khouri|1990}}]]
The painting is located in [[Qasr Amra]] (also transcribed "Quseir Amra", literally "little palace of Amra"), an Umayyad desert structure and a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]<ref name=unesco>{{cite web|title=Quseir Amra|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/327|author=UNESCO|work=World Heritage List}}</ref> about {{convert|85|km|mi}} east of [[Amman]] and {{convert|21|km|mi}} southwest of the [[Azraq Wetland Reserve]], [[Jordan]].{{sfn|Khouri|1990}} The complex has several frescoes painted on its walls.{{sfn|Khouri|1990}} The remoteness and size of the structure suggest that it served as a desert retreat for Umayyad rulers at the time.{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}}

The painting is on the southern end of the west portion of the main wall.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=197}}{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}} Along with other works in the complex, it was cleaned and preserved in the 1970s by a team from the [[National Archaeological Museum of Spain]].{{sfn|Khouri|1990}}

Historian Elizabeth Drayson estimated the earliest possible date for the painting to be 710, the year of the accession of Roderic{{snd}}one of the kings portrayed in the painting{{snd}}and the latest to be 750, the year of [[Abbasid Revolution]] that overthrew the Umayyads.{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=121}} The artist who painted the fresco is unknown. The patron who commissioned the building, including the painting, was likely one of the caliphs [[al-Walid I]] (reigned 705–715), [[al-Walid II]] ({{r.}}{{nbsp}}743–744) or [[Yazid III]] ({{r.}}{{nbsp}}744).{{sfn|Baker|1980}} It might have been commissioned after the patron became caliph, or before, when the patron was a member of the caliph's family and held the position of governor or heir.{{sfn|Baker|1980}}

The complex, long familiar to local nomads, was discovered (to the West) by the Czech scholar [[Alois Musil]] in 1898.{{sfn|Khouri|1990}} Musil and his companion, Austrian artist [[Alphons Leopold Mielich]], tried to remove the painting from the site, causing permanent damage.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=198}} A fragment of the painting, containing labels and partial crowns of two of the figures, is now in the {{Interlanguage link multi|Museum of Islamic Art (Berlin)|de|3=Museum für Islamische Kunst (Berlin)|lt=Museum of Islamic Art}}, [[Berlin]].{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=12}}{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=203}}<ref>Museum für Islamische Kunst, Berlin, inv. no. I.1265</ref>

Musil's 1907 publication ''Kusejr 'Amra''{{sfn|Musil|1907}} included a [[tracing (art)|tracing]] made by Mielich on the spot, Musil's interpretative copy made on the spot, Mielich's later reproduction, and Mielich's written description of the painting.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=12}}{{sfn|Fowden|2004|pp=203–204}} This publication included their observations made before much of the damage to the painting was done.{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}}{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=204}}

==Description==
[[File:Amra5.jpg|thumb|right|150px|A 1907 reproduction of the damaged painting<ref name="met"/>]]
The painting is badly damaged, partly due to the efforts by Alois Musil to remove it.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=198}} Large portions of the figures and their garments are not clearly visible. There are six rulers, or kings, standing facing the viewer in two rows of three.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=198}}{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}} Each king stretches out both hands with palms turned upwards. Inscriptions in Greek and Arabic above four of the figures, written in white letters on a blue background,{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=203}} identify them as:<ref name="met"/>{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}}
* ''Kaisar''/''Qaysar'' ("[[Caesar (title)|Caesar]]"), the Byzantine emperor, face not visible, wearing imperial robes and tiara,{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=204}}{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}} 
* ''Rodorikos''/''Ludhriq'', [[Roderic]], the [[Visigoths|Visigothic]] king of Hispania, barely visible, except for the tip of his helmet and robes,{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=204}}{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}}
* [[Khosrow (word)|''Khosroes''/''Kisra'']], the Sasanian emperor, appearing young with curly hair, wearing a crown, a cloak, and shoes,{{sfn|Fowden|2004|pp=204–205}}{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}} and
* ''[[Armah|Najashi]]'', the Negus of the Kingdom of Aksum, in a light garment with red [[stole (shawl)|stole]].{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=205}}{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}}

The labels were already fragile when Musil found it, and many of the labels were lost when he and Mielich tried to clean the painting and remove it from the site.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=203}} However, Musil's 1907 publication provided his reproduction of the labels before the damage.{{sfn|Fowden|2004|p=204}} Apart from the four rulers, no identification remains visible for the other two rulers. Possible identities speculated for them include the [[emperor of China]],<ref name="met"/> a [[Khan (title)|Turkic leader]],<ref name="met"/> and an Indian ruler.{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}}

Alongside the painting of the six kings, on the same wall, is a painting of a woman with the Greek word [[Nike (mythology)|ΝΙΚΗ]] ''Nikē'' "Victory" above her.{{sfn|Baker|1980}}{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=119}} Opposite the painting, towards which the six rulers are gesturing, is a painting of a man seated on a throne. Above this man is an inscription containing a blessing on a person whose name is now invisible.{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=119}}

==Interpretation==
The intent and meaning of the painting are unclear, and disputed by scholars.{{sfn|Grabar|1954|p=185}} The highly diverse interpretations of the painting are partly due to the loss of information from the damage.{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=117}}

According to Islamic art consultant Patricia Baker, the [[Greek language|Greek]] word for "victory" appearing nearby suggests that the image was meant to suggest the caliph's supremacy over his enemies.{{sfn|Baker|1980}} Betsy Williams of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] suggested that the six figures are depicted in supplication, presumably towards the caliph who would be seated in the hall.<ref name="met"/> Other scholars, including Arabic [[epigraphist]] [[Max van Berchem]] and architectural historian [[K. A. C. Creswell]], argued that the six rulers are a representation of the defeated enemies of Islam.{{sfn|Grabar|1954|p=185}} [[Iranologist]] and archaeologist [[Ernst Herzfeld]] argued that the painting is an Umayyad copy or version of the Sassanian "Kings of the Earth" located at [[Kermanshah]], as recorded by [[Yaqut al-Hamawi]] in his work ''[[Mu'jam al-Buldan]]'' (''Dictionary of Countries'').{{sfn|Grabar|1954|p=185}} Art historian [[Oleg Grabar]] interpreted the painting as an attempt to convey the idea that the Umayyad dynasty was the descendant and heir of the dynasties it had defeated.{{sfn|Drayson|2006|p=121}}{{sfn|Grabar|1954}}

